          <text x="775" y="72" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(57,255,142,0.4)" font-size="9" font-family="monospace">TupleSpace</text>
          <rect x="735" y="88" width="75" height="20" rx="4" fill="#12121e" stroke="rgba(57,255,142,0.2)" stroke-width="1"/>
          <text x="772" y="102" text-anchor="middle" fill="#39ff8e" font-size="8" font-family="monospace">DataWorker</text>

          <!-- Encrypted channel between peers -->
          <line x1="620" y1="67" x2="715" y2="67" stroke="#39ff8e" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="6 3" filter="url(#em-cf-glow)"/>
          <text x="667" y="60" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(57,255,142,0.4)" font-size="8" font-family="monospace">&#128274; CRDT sync</text>

          <!-- Cross-peer claim arrow -->
          <line x1="735" y1="98" x2="620" y2="74" stroke="#39ff8e" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="4 3" marker-end="url(#em-cf-arrow-green)" filter="url(#em-cf-glow)"/>

          <text x="660" y="150" text-anchor="middle" fill="rgba(57,255,142,0.5)" font-size="10" font-family="monospace" font-style="italic">goals cross the wire. agents converge from anywhere.</text>
        </svg>
        <div class="compare-pair">
          <div class="compare-side compare-them">
            <span class="compare-tag">Them</span>
            <p>OpenAI Swarm runs agents in a single process with handoffs; coordination dies at the process boundary. AutoGen's multi-agent conversations happen in one runtime. MCP connects tools across machines but agents stay local: the tools travel, the goals don't. No framework lets agents on different machines work on the same goal without a central server holding the state.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="compare-side compare-abjects">
            <span class="compare-tag compare-tag-abjects">Abject</span>
            <p>Goals are CRDTs that sync across peers through encrypted WebRTC channels with no central server. Kill a peer and the goal survives on every other peer that subscribed. The workers crossing the wire aren't all LLM agents; some are programs that agents spawned to do the grunt work.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Row 3: Failure & Recovery -->
